Getters and setters have frequently been criticized for not adhering to proper Object-Oriented (OO) principles. However, it is noteworthy that a significant portion of OO code incorporates extensive use of getters and setters. This raises the question: when are getters and setters justified? Do developers actively seek to minimize their usage? Are they, in fact, overused in contemporary programming practices? In languages that support properties—such as my preferred language—these constructs are essentially equivalent to getters and setters from an OO methodology standpoint, albeit with more elegant syntax. 

To shed light on the criticism surrounding getters and setters, I've compiled several sources that highlight various perspectives on this topic. These sources include:
- [JavaWorld Article on Getters and Setters](http://www.javaworld.com/javaworld/jw-09-2003/jw-0905-toolbox.html)
- [Typical Programmer Blog](http://typicalprogrammer.com/?p=23)
- [C2 Wiki Discussion on Accessors](http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?AccessorsAreEvil)
- [Darron Schall's Blog](http://www.darronschall.com/weblog/2005/03/no-brain-getter-and-setters.cfm)
- [Adam Bien's Insights](http://www.adam-bien.com/roller/abien/entry/encapsulation_violation_with_getters_and)

The core of the criticism can be summarized succinctly: getters and setters enable external manipulation of an object's internal state, which fundamentally violates the principle of encapsulation. Ideally, only the object itself should have the authority to manage its internal state. 

To illustrate this point, consider the following procedural code example:

```c
struct Fridge {
    int cheese;
}

void go_shopping(Fridge fridge) {
    fridge.cheese += 5;
}
```

Now, compare it to a mutator version:

```csharp
class Fridge {
    int cheese;

    void set_cheese(int _cheese) { cheese = _cheese; }
    int get_cheese() { return cheese; }
}

void go_shopping(Fridge fridge) {
    fridge.set_cheese(fridge.get_cheese() + 5);
}
```

In this instance, the introduction of getters and setters complicates the code significantly without providing adequate encapsulation. Since the internal state is exposed to other objects, the benefits of implementing getters and setters become questionable. This topic has been previously explored in discussions on Stack Overflow, which can be found here:
- [Stack Overflow Discussion on Getters and Setters](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/565095/java-are-getters-and-setters-evil)
- [Another Stack Overflow Thread](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/996179)

